{"/service/ndnp/curiv/batch_curiv_roseheath_ver01/data/sn92070146/00414188849/1937122201/0276.xml":{"full_text":"HANK DEBITS\nTUESDAY\n$330,651.12\nBUILDING PERMITS\nTO DATE THIS TEAR\n$272,160\nVOLUME XXXVI; No. 252.\nNORTHEND CLEANUP ORDERED\nAutoist's Head\nCrushed as Car\nCrashes, Upsets\nAMBLING\nJtVEPORTER\nSetting a Precedent\nDoris Baker was married this\nweek to George Robertson. Last\nmonth another girl who lived at\nthe same place where Doris stayed\nbefore the marriage also entered\nthe state of wedded bliss. RR can\nnot help wondering if the fact\nthat both girls lived a the Ernest\nLovesee home had anything to do\nwith it.\n1 o\nYear After Year\u2014\nThe old buggy Oliver Wendell\nHolmes wrote so much poetry about\nhad nothing on the Christmas tree\nholder loaned to the Safeway store\nhere by Charles Free, jr. If you\nthink a Christmas tree holder is\njust a couple of crossed boards, or\na wire gadget of some kind, you\u2019d\nbetter revise your opinion. This\none was brought to this country\nby Free\u2019s grandmother 75 years\nago, and has operated just about\nevery year since then without re\npairs of any kind. It\u2019s a beautiful\nsilvered revolving gadget that keeps\nthe tree turning, anl somewhere in\nside there is a music box that rings\nout merrily with \u201cSilent Night\u201d\nand other Christmas tunes from\nGermany. It almost makes you\nwish you celebrated Christmas as\nthey did 75 years ago.\n\u2014o\nTragedy\u2014\nOn Olive avenue Tuesday after\nnoon there was a limp white form,\nlife snuffed from it by some care\nless motorist. Gathered about the\nlifeless body of their dog-friend\nv.ere three little boys. Forgotten\nwas the Christmas season, forgot\nten the toys that will come. They\nknew only, at that moment, that\nfate can be a pretty cruel tning.\nThere w\u2019as a lump in RR\u2019s throat\ncs he passed by.\n\u2014o\nDark Conspiracy\u2014\nThere was dirty work afoot at\nthe Lions club meeting in El Cen\ntro Tuesday. Here's what happen\ned, in chronological order.\nDr. O. H. Van Eman appeared\non a special mission. He an\nnounced the discovery of a tifty\nbaby, left an orphan at birth, and\nsuggested this being Christmas\nand all \u2014that someone in the club\nshould take the Infant and care\nfor it until a permanent home\nshould be discovered for it.\nThe club was receptive. But they\ncouldn\u2019t agree who was to have\nthe child. Finally someone sug\ngested drawing lots. The saps were\nprepared. They were passed around.\nHugo Miller got the different\none.\nHugo declared himself not un\npleased at the prospect of having\na bafcjy in his home.\nThen the baby was brought in.\nIt was the cutest little pickaninny\nyou ever saw.\nFurhermore. it was quite a while\nbefore Hugo learned that the cnild\u2019s\nparents, both living, wouldn\u2019t give\nthe little feller up for all the mil\nlions there are.\nSWING EXPECTS\nCOURT TO DROP\nBAN ON POWER\nA temporary injunction against the federal gov jrn\nment and the Imperial Irrigation District to prevent full\nconstruction of the All American canal power system will\nbe dismissed by the District of Columbia supreme court\nin January, Phil Swing believes. Swing, special represen-\ntative of the irrigation district to<\nWashington, told directors that an\nticipated favorable action by the\nUnited States Supreme Court in\nthe Alabama and Duke Power com\npany eases should result fn dis\nmissal of the temporary injunction\nin the Nevada-CaTlfornia Electric\ncorporation suit against the gov\nernment and the district, because\nof the similarity of the actions.\nThe prediction was voiced by\nSwing during a brief visit to Im\nperial Valley en route to San\nDiego, where he will spend the\nChristmas holiday with ills family.\nQuestions asked by U. S. Supreme\nCourt members when they heard\nluP argument.-, in the Alabama* and\nDuke cases Dec. 6, 7 and 8 in\ndicated a favorable attitude to' the\nIMPERIAL VALLEY PRESS\nPassenger, Driver\nOf Other Auto\nUninjured\nThe death of Apolonio\nMarroguin, 73, in an auto\nmobile accident on the Holt\nville-Imperial highway early\nWednesday morning, bring\ning the traffic death total to 45, one\nless than last year\u2019s total.\nMarrogum\u2019s head was cnished by\nthe car he was driving as it over\nturned after a collision with\na milk truck. The truck was driven\nby Fred Buckel of Holtville, who\nescaped without injury. Francisco\nMacias, a passenger in Marroguln\u2019s\ncar, was uninjured.\nThe accident occurred four and\na half miles northwest of Holtville\nat 6:45 am. Wednesday a short\ndistance west of the point Where\nthe old highway crosses the rail\nway tracks. Highway Patrolman\nPaul Brown said.\nDeputy Coroner Herbert Hughes\nordered the oody of the Mexican\ntaken to the Fields undertaking\nestablishment in Holtville. An in\nquest was scheduled for 3:30 o'clock\nWednesday afternoon.\nSTORES STAY\nOPEN TO 9 P.M.\nUNTIL DEC. 25\nTo give late choppers in Im\nperial Valley an opportunity to\nship long and late. El Centro\nstores will remain open until\n9 p.m. every evening until Christ\nmas.\nHoltville Youth\nSent to Jail in\nDelinquency Case\nL.vnton Wade, Holtville youth,\nwas sentenced to the county jail\nfor one year after Judge R. D. Me\nPherrin denied his application for\nprobation in superior court Wed\nnesday.\nThe youth formerly had pleaded\nguilty to contributing to the delin\nquency of a minor. The court per\nmitted a stay of execution of he\ncommitment order until Thursday\nmorning to permit Wade to put his\naffairs in order-\nColder Weather\nSeen for Valley\nLower temperatures in Imperial\nValley within the next three days\nwere predicted by Woodrow C. Ja\ncobs. meteorologist, Wednesday with\nthermometers slated to fall below\n32 degrees in colder sections of\nthe valley Wednesday night.\nTemperatures as low as 30 de\ngrees were recorded in the valley\nTuesday night.\nIncreasing high cloudiness was\nforecast for Wednesday and Thurs\nday.\nWet Christmas for\nSan Diego Forecast\nSAN DIEGO. Dee. 22. (UP)\u2014Pos\nsibility of a rainy, wet Christmas\nwas seen in the prediction of the\nU. S. weather bureau here today\nthat rain would fall for at least the\nnext 24 hours.\nr\ngovernment. Swing explained. A\nfavorable decision would r.pprov\nthe right of the federal government\nto loan money to municipal agen\ncies for construction of municipal\npewer systems in competition with\nprivate companies.\nA precedent set by the U. S.\nSupreme Court would automatical\nly be followed by the District of\nColumbia Supreme C urt in the\nsuit against the government and\nthe district, involving the same\nissues, Swing said.\nThe suit against the Imperial\ncounty iX'Wer project is aimed to\nprevent general distribution of\npublic power. It does not inter\nfere with the rural electrification\nprogram, now' under way.\nCarrying Full UNITED PRESS Day and Night Leased Wire Service and Features of NEA, Inc., Central Prens Association, McNaught Syn\ndicate, King Features, and Complete Valley News Gathered by the Largest Editorial Staff in Southeastern California.\nMaster Mind'\nat Rest\nGen. Erich I.udendorff, \u201cmaster\nmind\" of the German World\nWar army, who was given a\nslate funeral Wednesday with\nFuehrer Adolph Hitler and Mar\nshal Werner von Blomberg, war\nminister, present. The general\u2019s\nbody lay in state for five hours\nat the vietory gate of the eity\nwhile ownspeople filed by. Then\nit was taken to the Flederrnhalle\nwhere Hitler\u2019s \u201cbeer cellar\u201d\nPutsch, in which Ludcndnrff\nplayed a leading part, was start\ned, for the funeral service.\nNAVAL BOMBING\nTESTS ALONG\nBORDER SLATED\nI\nU.S. Warns Private Fliers\nBetween Sa;i Diego.\nMexicali\nWASHINGTON, Doc. 22.\n(UP) \u2014Navy officials said\ntoday that notices have been\n1 issue d to commercial air\nlines and private filers to\nstay clear of territory along the\nMexican border between San Die\ngo Cal., and Mexicali, Mex., dur\ning contemplated bombing tests\nby navy planes.\nOfficials said the \"stand clear\u201d\nnotices were for a temporary pe\nriod only, during the bombing\ntest. No permanent regulations of\nthis character are contemplated,\nit was said.\nARMED LAUNCHES PATROL\nS. D. BAY IN SECRET MOVE\nLIGHT JUDGES\nSTUDY NOTES\nChristmas Lighting judges Wed\nnesday were comparing notes prior\nto announcing the winners in the\nPost-Press Christmas Lighting con\ntest in the three divisions embrac\ning small homes, medium homes\nand large homes.\nFollowing the request of Christ\nmas Lighting contest officials, most\nresidents of El Centro kept their\ndisplays lighted from 5 to 9 o\u2019clock\neach night. They were urged to\ncontinue this practice during the\nrest of the week.\nMeanwhile everyone who has not\nalready done so should fill out the\nblank published elsewhere in this\npaper so the Post-Press may publish\na complete list of the homes lighted\nin El Centro's brightest Christmas.\nSaying Merry Christmas, in Lights\n(Five Cents Per Copy) EL CENTRO, CALIF., WEDNESDAY, DECEMBER 22, 1937.\nSTRIKE ON\nCANAL JOB\nHITS SNAC\nPicket Lines Broken, Union Men Drift\nBack to Work; Walkout \u2018Not So\nGood\u2019 Say Officials\nYUMA, Dec. 22. (Special)\u2014Picket lines were broken\nand union laborers and craftsmen filtered back to work\ntoday on the T. A. Allen sub-contract at the Pilot Knob\nwasteway on the All American canal, where a strike was\ncalled Monday morning by Yuma labor leaders.\nAt the Yuma labor temple union-*\nofficials said the strike was \"not\nso good.\u201d\nSheriff Robert W Ware, charg\ning that the union had violated\na gentlemen\u2019s agreement, dispersed\npickets. The union agreed Monday\nnight, the sheriff said, that only\none picket from each craft repre\nsented in the strike would be sta\ntioned at thp job. That afternoon\nbetween 20 and 25 pickets were\nchased off when they congregated\nnear the scene ol operations and\njeered those stfll working. Eight\npickets were ordered away lrom\nthe road leading to the job. where,\nthe sheriff said, they attempted\nto intimidate men reporting for\nwork.\nThree men were ordered away\nfrom picket posts Tuesday after\nnoon. They were distributing cop\nies of a labor union newspaper\npublished in Yuma.\nSix carpenters, a7l union mem\nbers, reported for work on the Al\nlen job Tuesday. Two more came\nback today. Laborers in other\ncrafts followed their example.\nMany union members who had\nstayed off the job because they\nrefused to pass through picket\nlines now feel at liberty to resume\nwork, the contractor explained.\nThe contract was proceeding un\n1 tier schedule. He has a sufficient\ncrew now' to perform the work.\nAllen said, and expects more men\nt<\u2014 report back on the job\n\u2019the week is ended.\nA union attempt to tie up the\nI job by halting delivery of sand\nand gravel failed when members\nI of the Teamsters Union here e-\nr used to strike in sympathy. The\nteamsters were under orders from\ntheir locals to continue hauling\nmaterials to the Allen job \u201d\"ti!\nwritten orders to the conrary are\ndelivered. Officials of the Team\nsters Union refused to join the\nstrike because they had not beer,\nconsulted before it was called.\nOfficials of striking unions also\nrttempted to induce a federal labor\n(Continued on Page 2 Column 5\u00bb\nSAN DIEGO, Cal., Dec. 22. (UP)\u2014The navy simulated\nactual wartime conditions in San Diepo bay today during\nsudden and secret fleet maneuvers.\nA concentration of destroyer units apparently had\nbeen effected. For the second consecutive night, armed\nlaunches patrolled the bay, where'\neight squadrons of the destroyer\nflotilla and the heavier cruiser div\nisions lay at anchor.\nThree fishing craft were halted\nas they sought to enter the bay\nduring the night. One of these\ncraft, it was reported, carried a\nJapanese crew.\nIn the Long Beach anchorage a\ndozen destroyers wallowed. They\nwere ordered up from San Diego\nafter an emergency mobilization\nwhich recalled officers and crews\nirom holiday shore leaves.\nNaval authorities were tight\nlipped as to the pur|>ose of the\nmaneuvers. They announced mere-\nly that destroyer units \"had been\nordered north \u201cfor training pur\nLABOR PEACE\nNEGOTIATIONS\nIN COLLAPSE\nRival Factions Intensify\nDrive For Increase\nIn Membership\nWASHINGTON, Dec. 22.\n(UP) \u2014The American Fed\neration of Labor and the\nCommittee for Industrial\nOrganization i n ten s i f ied\ntheir drives for membership today\nin a finish fight for a control\nci the labor movement.\nEmbittered by the collapse of\nnegotiations between special peace\ncommittees, the rival leaders ad\ndressed recriminations to each\nother and there were in\ndications that the number of juris\ndicional raids and boycotts be\ntween the two groups would be\nincreased.\nFederal officials were worried.\nPiesident Roosevelt expressed dis\nappointment over the termination\not peace talks.\nIt was believed that dual union\nization drives would be concen\ntrated in toe 1 fol\u2019ow(ng fields: A.\nF. of L.\u2014cereal, flour, aluminum,\ncement; CIO\u2014-textiles, oil, elec\ntrical manufacture in the midwest,\nand shipbuilding.\nMeanwhile the CIO and the Fed\neration prepared to battle the\neffects of the business recession\nupon their members.\nJohn L. Lewis, CIO chairman,\ndiscussed with Works Progress Ad\nministration officials, including\nAssistant Administrator David\nRiles, methods of feeding unem\nployed workers and their families.\nThe CIO is conducting a private\ndrive to cooperate with federal\nlelief administration.\nposes.\u201d\nLaunches, manned by machine\ngun crews of bluejackets, maintain\ned an all-night vigil at San Diego,\ncruising in and out of the stream\nwhere warships rolled at anchor.\nDestroyer squadrons were more\nclosely guarded than cruisers, which\nhad not been involved in the man\neuver so far. No civilians were per\nmitted to board destroyers. News\nboys and salesmen who occasion\nally come aboard at night, were\nsearched before being allowed on\ncruisers.\nReason for the mysterious moves\nwas unknown but some sources be\nlieved tie maneuvers were merely\na drill to test the fleet in an emer\ngency.\nPeace Leader\nPasses\nFrank Kellogg, former secre\ntary of state, and famous expo\nnent of world peace, who died\nTuesday night of pneumonia.\nHis death was on the eve of his\n81st birthday.\nFRANK KELLOGG,\nEX-SECRETARY\nOF STATE, DIES\nPneumonia Takes Life of\nPeace Leader Near\n81st Birthday\nST. PAUL, Minn., Dec.\n22. (UP) \u2014Frank Billings\nKellogg, world dipomat, for\nmer secretary of state and\nco-sponsor of the Kellogg-\nBriand peace pact, died last night\n\u2014\u2022the eve of his 81st birthday.\nHe died at his home from pneu-\nI fnonis which developed Sunday.\nThe disease was complicated by\nI cerebral thrombosis, his physician\ni said.\nKellogg leaves his widow, the\nformer Clara Cook of St. Louis.\nShe and his law partner, CTuy\nChase, and Dr. J. A. Lepak, were\npresent when death came. He had\nnr children.\nLepak said the statesman fell\ninto a complete coma Tuesday night\nand did not recover consciousness.\nDeath came at 7:14.\nThe pact which Kellogg com\npleted with Arisfide Briand of\nest achievement. The document\nContinued on Page 2 Column 3)\nMYSTERY NOTE\nIN HEALY DEATH\nHOLLYWOOD. Dec. 22. (UP)\nTed Healy. famous stage and screen\ncomedian, died of heart disease and\nlung congestion, with no evidence\nof injuries from foul play, Coroner\nP. A. Nance announced today\nA badly discolored eye and two\ntiny silver clips closing a cut over\nthe other eye had prompted police\ntoday to order the autopsy on the\ncomedian who died y\u00abterday.\nPolice aho investigated reports\nof a fight Healy allegedly engaged\nIn Sunday .light in a fashionable\nnight dub.\nPolice had questioned film stars\nand others who were in the Tro\ncadero club Sunday night when the\ncomedian was there celebrating the\nbirth of his first child.\nAttracting much attention as one\ne) the most attractive Chris\u2019mas\nlighting displays in El Centro\u2019s\nnerth-side residential district is\nthe Fred Nebel-Thau home at\n1042 Park avenue, >hewn as it\nappeared Tuesday night.\nPOST-PRESS ENGRAVING\nWestmorland\nCommanded to\nDrive Out Vice\nSheriff Ware Decrees Reform After\nProtests by Residents; Says\nMove Out \u2018Or Else\u2019\nWestmorland vice establishments, objects of grand\njury displeasure early this year, must close and all women\ninhabiting them must leave the community immediately,\nSheriff Robert W. Ware ordered Wednesday.\nThe sheriff issued the order, he said, at the request of\nlarge numbers of residents of the<\nWestmorland area who repeatedly\nvoiced dissatisfaction with vice\nconditions in the north-end city.\nHe said the grand jury edit to\nWestmorland city officials ordered\nthe clean-up by the municipality it\nself. In the event the city did not\nfellow instruction, he said, county\nofficials were ordered to step in.\nIn a letter to Chief of Police Ed\nDickerson. Ware asked the officer\nto close all vice establishments\nwithin 24 hours and clear the\nwomen out within the same period.\nIn the event the request is ignored.\nWare said, he and his deputies will\ntake over the task.\n\u201cCertain of the so-called hangers\non around the vice establishments\nin Westmorland,\u201d the sheriff de-\nclared \"cause law enforcement of\nficers trouble and complicate the\ntask of keeping law and order.\n\u201cI asked the cooperation of West\nmorland officers and trust the whole\nthing may be settled within the\nnext day or two and the district\ncleared as requested.\u201d\nWare\u2019s action climaxed months of\nunrest regarding vice-conditions in\nthe city which were brought to the\nattention of the public at the time\nof the Culberson trial in superior\ncourt. The Culberson ca. c e involv\ning the hiring of two juvenile girls\nin a house managed by Mr. and\nMrs. Andy Culberson, Negroes.\nThe Imperial county grand jury\ndelved into the question and order\ned city authorities to clean up the\nplace or the grand jury would order\ncounty authorities to do so. One\npolitical shake-up after another\nrocked the north-end city while\nmunicipal authorities attempted to\ncomply with the grand jury order-\nCity employes were discharged,\nothers hired, and several city coun\ncilmen resigned within the last\nseveral months.\nPicket Parades\nAt Calexico Cafe\nCALEXICO. Dec. 22 (UP)\u2014One\nunion picket is parading in front\nof a cafe and bar as a protest to\nthe open shop maintained by the\nproprietors.\nThe picket wears a card bearing\nthe words. \u201cThis place is unfair to\nunion labor\" Hie card has been in\nevidence in front of the place at\nintervals since Saturday. No con\nfusion has resulted and the cafe\nand bar are operating as usual,\nofficers sad.\nADMINISTRATION\nSET FOR BATTLE\nON BUSINESS AID\nWASHINGTON, Dec. 22. (UP) Administration lead\ners cleared away the wreckage of President Roosevelt's\nspecial session program today to prepare for a struggle\nover control of an aid-to-business legislative campaign\nstarting in January. The regular session of congress ap-\npeared certain to witness sharps\nconflict between administration\nleaders seeking to encourage busi\nness with the least possible sacri\nfice to the New Deal program and\ncongressional rebels seeking more\ndrastic legislative action at the\nexpense of the New Dealers.\nThe chief points at issue Will be\nthe extent to which congress will\ngc in legislation for tax relief, re\nvival of the wages and hours bill,\nextension of governmental power\nHOW LEGISLATION STOOD AS\nCONGRESS ENDED SESSION\nWASHINGTON, Dec. 22. I UP)\u2014Congress adjourned with major\nlegislation in this status:\nCROP CONTROL\u2014In conference.\nHOUSING ACT AMENDMENTS\u2014In conference.\nMAXIMUM HOURS AND MINIMUM WAGES\u2014Paaaed by *rn\nate: recommitted and virtually killed by house.\nTAX REVWION\u2014Being drafted in house ways and means\ncommittee.\nREGIONAL PLANNING\u2014Under consideration in houae rivers\nand harbors committee and senate agriculture committee.\nANTI-LYNCHING\u2014Passed by house; comes before senate Jan. I.\nGOVERNMENT REORGANIZATION\u2014Senate ready to consid\ner full program when anti-lynching hi disposed of; houae approred\npartial program.\nANTI-TRUST\u2014No action in either house.\nButter: I,<M Angelea 17; But\nterfat, Imperial Valley, f.fcb. ranch\ngrade A 47; manufacturing milk\n40; route gathered cream 364 e\nL. A. Hay; U. 8. No. I $18.50-\n$20,50. No 2 leafy 118.-1ft.56. No.\n2. leafy $16.50-17.\nMinneapolis Flax; Dec., s2.o2'*\nPHONE 300\nJAPAN OFFICER\nREMOVED OVER\nRAID INCIDENT\nExtremist Relieved of His\nCommand 1 Gets Blame\nFor U. S. Attacck\nSHANGHAI, Dec. 22.\n(UP) \u2014Col. Shingoro Haah\nimoto, commanding Japa\nnese troops along the upper\nYangtze, has been removed\nfrom his post as the result of troop\nattacks on United States and\nBritish warships. Americans arriv\ning here asserted today.\nIt was asserted that Hashimoto,\npolitically powerful firebrand of the\nextremist element in the Japanese\narmy, was relieved of his command\nlast Saturday and replaced \u2022by a\nfellow colonel who \u201cshowed a much\nmore cooperative spirit.\"\nThe Americans, who arrived here\nfrom Wuhu. did not know whether\nHashimoto had been recalled or\ntransferred to another command.\nForeign military experts suggested\nthat he probably was given an\nother command. His mere removal,\nthey said, would be a sufficient in\ndication of the concern of the Japa\nnese army at attacks on united\nStates and British ships.\nHashimoto was regarded by for\neigner here as the man really re\nsponsible for the machine gunning\nof the American gunboat Panay,\nas it sank after it was abandoned,\nby Japanese troops in launches.\nCol. Hashimoto is alleged to have\nsaid, after attacks by his troops\nDecember 13 on the British gun\nboat Ladybird and the Panay, that\nhe had orders to fire on all ships\nin the Yangtse regardless of na\ntionality. It was denied afterward\nthat Hashimoto had any such order.\n63 Cars Full of\nLettuce Go Out\nSixty-three cars of lettuce were\nshipped frohi valley stations Tues\nday to boost shipments for the\nyear to 263 cars.\nOne car of peas, two of mixed\nvegetables, one of spinach> and two\nof greens were also shipped from\nthe valley Tuesday.\ndevelopment, reorganization of the\nexecutive branch, and foreign policy.\nMany legislators believed the out\ncome would bear heavily on the\nfuture of the New Deal program\ngenerally.\nThe special session ended yester\nday without completing any item\non Mr Roosevelt's legislative pro\ngram. The final decisions In Janu\nary may depend on the ability of\nthe administration lb combat the\ncurrent business recession\nTHE POST-PRESS","height":"29664","width":"23432"}}
